e Miller explains their puzzling behavior today. More broadly, she argues that the transformative historical experience of a large category of actors-ex-colonies, who have previously been neglected in the study of international relations-can be used as a method to categorize states in the international system. In the process Miller offers a more inclusive way to analyze states than do traditional theories of international relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aImperialismxPsychological aspects. 0aInternational relationsxPsychological aspects. 4aChina. 4aColonialism. 4aIndia. 4aforeign policy. 4ahistory. 4aideology. 4arising power. 4aterritorial sovereignty. 4atrauma. 4avictim. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804788434zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788434423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804788434.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles